This paper focuses on analyzing customer service dialogue on Twitter and developing a model to automate customer service interactions. Therefore, it is likely to belong to the sub-category of Computational Linguistics (cs.CL) as it involves natural language processing and dialogue modeling. It also involves machine learning and data-driven approaches, which could fall under Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) and Information Retrieval (cs.IR) sub-categories. Additionally, the paper mentions characterizing differences between customer and agent behavior, which could fall under Cybersecurity (cs.CY) and Software Engineering (cs.SE) sub-categories. Finally, the paper discusses predicting conversation outcomes, which could fall under Systems and Control (cs.SY) and Sound and Music Computing (cs.SD) sub-categories.
